outputs.description: Advocacy for child rights                agencies, artistes, sports people and the private sector are engaged in partnershipspromoting the rights of all girls and boys in a gender sensitive way (OT 796)

By 2016, girls and boys (0-5) living in households in the poorest communities in 9 countries (Antigua and Barbuda, Dominica,Grenada, Montserrat, St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, St. Lucia, Trinidad & Tobago and Anguilla) have access toquality developmental and education services
By 2016, duty bearers in the education sector and rights-holders have knowledge and skills to prevent violence against children inschool-based settings.
By 2016 duty bearers in the protection sector and rights holders have knowledge and skills to protect children from harm andviolence
By 2016 duty bearers and right holders have increased awareness of children's rights issues in the Eastern Caribbean Area
By 2016, national and regional partnerships and networks are strengthened to support knowledge sharing on child rights andpromote a culture of M & E .
By 2016, all 12 countries have submitted any due and outstanding State reports on CRC and ratified CRC Optional protocols
By 2016, 5 countries have strengthened national systems (admin data and survey plan) for the production of social data on childrenin at least the Child Protection and Education sectors
By 2016,  3 countries and territories in the sub-region have incorporated child sensitive indicators in their national developmentplanning framework
By 2016, duty bearers have increased national capacities to effectively implement a child and gender sensitive budgeting approachin national budgets
By 2016, duty bearers have new standards, knowledge and abilities for developing improved children protection systems to preventand respond to violence, exploitation and abuse against children.
By 2016, duty bearers in 12 countries have national capacity to support the adoption of rights-based child protection legislation.
By 2016, duty bearers responsible for civil registration have the knowledge and skills to achieve timely, free and fully completedbirth registration and certification.
Child centred, equity focused and costed national sector plans reflecting regional frameworks in place in 9 countries  (OT 208)

By 2016 duty bearers in 8 countries have increased capacity, supported with policy frameworks, to employ positive disciplinary andlearning practices in student-centred teaching and learning environments within school effectiveness/child friendly schoolsframework
